<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-10-13T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-10-13T03:00:00-05:00" n="508" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d508">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163/65: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-10-13T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">October 13,
                                        1926—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 13—9:35
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>476. My 453, October 5, 10 a.m. British Legation have received a telegram
                            from British missionary near Sianfu, dated October 12th, indicating that
                            all British and American missionaries who desired to leave are safely
                            out of Sianfu. American military officer will not therefore proceed to
                            Sianfu unless report proves incorrect.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>